Democritus had asserted that the heavier atoma overtook the lighter in their downward course, and thus initiated the collision which finally resulted in a general vortical movement. Epicurus retaining the same crude view of‘up’and ‘down’ held that each atem moved with equal speed and that they could only meet by the'inherent sels-movement of the atoms, which enabled them to swerve from the rigid vertieal line, and he found a confir- mation of this indeterminate movement of the atoma in the free will of man. In other respects there is little difference between the physical views of Democritus and Epicurus. Both held that there were innumerable worlds continually coming into being and passing out of being in the inlinitude of space.
